History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago and initially had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the fusion of four firms whose history was linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "higher" ones, the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who had presided over the Society's Supervisory Board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
The leader then made the shadow to the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that have been based until now on the identity and culture of society.
Watson led the Kusqu' firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all the possible machines for business and trade - from cheese and meat slicers to the register boxes.
