How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travels to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (the two in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A large exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was authorized to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a trend for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even in the context of socialist countries.
If Czechoslovak wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, an invitation letter was required if the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, there was a need to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for travel to the west was denied to the "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs were buying and this habit has lasted so far.
The Czech voyages have since 1989 been a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days on vacation in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are unaware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the West has caused a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for long to the west by plane that everyone wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations put Czechs in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with itself its own food canned, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally enabled our tourists after decades of free purchasing of Western currency.
Our standard of living, as well as the average wage, have increased what has led to another important moment around 1997.
As a result of a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter links since 1997 which through contracts have greatly reduced the costs compared to what was before.
In the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free links with almost most developed countries around the world apart from the EU that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since then, as every year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to the distant hot countries, there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to settle fully in the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for vacation abroad including the related charges.
