Climate adversity has slowed down the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations for economic progress, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in return there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing billionaire losses for the agricultural sector, have limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report on ice-cream allocations from the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main affected crops were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has led to a steady increase in State unemployment, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, in the first three quarters of the year, an accelerated increase was observed, as during January to March 55 thousand 053 signalers were unemployed, with a 4.53 per cent rate of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, an increase of more than 74 thousand signalers unemployed, an increase from the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an unlawful way, it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and to use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad, to the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because they already have a lot of difficulty in getting work, these people remain here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment increase," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labour market is compounded by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails between the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works without being employed in any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for delaying the state is low wages, the entity has lower wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much less than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from declining economic activity and rising unemployment, in 2011 the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June, the State FDI reached $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to $5,43 thousand,312 in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by the tertiary sector companies.
Debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, in July, the Government of the State requested the approval of a 3-billion-weight credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600-billion-weight and no debt in any sector of the State economy was observed until November.
Responses
For employers' representatives, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrated a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year was really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, it has had to align the effort of everyone and above all the good already synchronized walk of this new government team, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as early-year ice-cream have retained the economy of the state and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced from several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that doesn't turn fast enough to generate economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year, we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the National Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that all the potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources be detonated," he says.
Much to be done
