MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetic protocol of obesity of children and adolescents' that will allow for the markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate whether or not they are entitled to attend the IMSS sport units in Valle de México, where evidence is being made to minors every Saturday starting at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Sportive Unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (State of Mexico East).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Unit Independence (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that it is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for Mexican children and young people to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It has detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weights, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight-taking in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that, in only six years, there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity in boys and 47 per cent in girls; with respect to overweight, there was also a dramatic increase', the IMSS specialist stressed.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of Indo-American hereditary status, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calorie), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which helps to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and avant-bras indicate the probability of suffering metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, each explaining the measures and changes in their lifestyle to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking over short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e., the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat paste with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid cassia
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signs that the pavement was solved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Mexico Valley, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement was adequate, the cases could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassia, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore, the formation of cassia.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behaviour.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid condition, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, adds it.
This means that in the streets, asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, consisting of small rocks bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the bed, he said, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, opined the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts on a last layer called bearing layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand, which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adherence to the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassia.
In the case of the formation of a case, he said, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage is not immediately occurring, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The National Research System member explained that the vehicle load is another important factor for the formation of cassia and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassia.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and help repair the cases easily and without having to use high temperatures.
