Japan Reborn After Earthquakes
GDP increases by 1.5% through domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy had been paralyzed, still convalescent after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo calculated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seemed to have diminished.
After three consecutive trimesters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at the annualized rate.
The second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by earthquakes and subsequent tsunamis.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1 per cent, compared to a decrease of 0.9% of the capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real incentive of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use gaps for zero croitre.
Japan has woke up mainly as a result of the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refuge values" elected by investors who fled the debt crisis in eurozone and the disturbing forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a plaque in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious reverse for a country whose economic flow line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, took responsibility for their weak results between July and September for the contribution of the yen.
While markets continue to sit in EU peripheral countries, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower custody.
