Only 9% of Canadians accept to talk to their doctor about conditions in which they want to die and make provisions to that end.
This is one of the conclusions of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts have participated in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when required, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
If Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "death medicine in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death".
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, we report the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the wish most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die at the hospital.
Overall, it is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said that there is no need to change the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, which have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on individuals who are not competent or who are not consenting.
On the contrary, yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-sponsor of the report, more cases of these overflows would be found in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in Support of euthanasia
Let us recall that 85% of Canadians have already expressed support for euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of the elderly or the disabled have less value.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, the respondents estimate that 41% of them should not be prosecuted.
