The North Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia through the Baltic Sea, entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with excitement.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly links Russia to Germany.
Simbolically, German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Netherlands counterpart Mark Rutte played together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the Saint Petersburg region to the Mecklenburg-Pomérania Land.
A second tube is due to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, i.e. the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has an air of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will actually deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding land crossings by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of weakening energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has barely seen a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are in decline in five years' time.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon in inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by Gazprom leaders, present in number at the gas arrival point in Lubmin.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine tube is made of concrete- won steel to protect it against the anchorage of ships.
It is based on the seabed, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mining fields from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to increase measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned for the outside of Sweden, but the project managers gave up when the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently settling off their coasts.
"In the event of damage, we stop passing the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas in the pipeline will therefore escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, driven by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigarette, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of one meter in diameter, and is driven by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, he provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without any repairs.
The traffic of the gas is simply driven by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), together with the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, known as Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company, for 20 renewable years, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their own expense, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, which are 4.5 metres high, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas at every passing hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand card.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to remake the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskin book is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, like oldies by time.
Yet, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a design note book but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (tupe skin) which designates a varnished cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
"Moleskine gave to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century " , says Maria Sebregondi, who has become responsible for the brand at Mode Mode.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
It is far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a portrait of the buyer because the notebook of notes seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginning, accounts for almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the bookstores, from the Fnac to the small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched an exhibition " Back" where architects or artists expose their own notebooks.
In August, she also launched a cover in Leopard, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Enjoying its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer hoops... The brand is on a wide range of media.
A success that has made it exciting: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was redeemed by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskin.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of persons with disabilities is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouragement?
"No, points out Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of persons with disabilities."
" The progress made for fifteen years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
" However, there is still a great deal to be done. "
It must be said that there are still many obstacles for disabled people before accessing employment.
They are rather older: 37% are older than 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that only complicate return to employment, which "constitutes the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the target brakes.
There remains the undit, the attitudes that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Engrepreneur Association for the City indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of the disability ", with " overrepresentation of wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities ".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, as set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, dated 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the establishments of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises of 100 to 199 employees.
